You are right - it is a circular dependency.

Despite you don&#39;t have this dependency at the object level (your object instances don&#39;t have links one to each other) you have general design circular dependency.
Java Compilers allow you to compile this code if it is within a single module, and will throw an compile-time error if you split it into several modules - circular dependencies are forbidden across modules.
Even if you could compile this code - such circular dependencies are a sign of poor hard coupled design which will be hard to maintain and expand.

In this particular situation, the main problem is that your `Customer` is aware of the type of the `DiscountCalcualtor` it should use, as well as the `DiscountCalculator` implementation depends on the `Customer`. It means that if you introduce a new `CustomerType` value, you should implement a new `DiscountCalculator` and tight this Calculator to a particular `Customer` inside `enum CustomerType`. If you redesign your Calculators and for example reduce implementations or add some specific ones, you should &quot;inform&quot; `Customer` by updating your `enum CustomerType`.

One change in your design lead to multiple changes in different parts of the system.

There are several ways to get rid of circular dependencies and make application design clean. Here are some ideas that you can apply to this situation:
1. Get rid of the `enum CustomerType` or at least remove all &quot;factory-related logic&quot; from the enum. `Customer` shouldn&#39;t be aware of `DiscountCalculator` and the structure of your application (it knows that your use a factory pattern to create `DiscountCalculator`). Add the factory method to `DiscountCalculator`, and make this class responsible for providing you with the right factory.
For example:
```
class DiscountCalculatorFactory {

  private DiscountCalculatorFactory() {}

  public static DiscountCalculator getDiscountCalculator(Customer customer) {
    CustomerType type = customer.getCustomerType();
    return switch (type) {
      case VIP -&gt; new VIPDiscountCalculator(customer);
      case REGULAR -&gt; new RegularDiscountCalculator(customer);
      default -&gt; throw new IllegalArgumentException(type.toString());
    };
  }
}
```
You can implement it in different ways, but the general idea - the `Customer` shouldn&#39;t be aware of the `DiscountCalculator` as well as of application structure and other plumbing code.

2. Do not recommend changing the implementation of `DiscountCalculator` and make it stateless by using `Customer` as an argument to your `public int calculateDiscount()`. It seems the easiest way, but you still have all the problems we discussed above, and circular dependency at the class level is in place - but they are more difficult to spot now. Also if we make the class stateless we lose some advantages of the OOP paradigm - encapsulation of both *data* and *methods* of processing.

