I found that the best solution for me is to convert the RGB values into [YIQ][1] values. As we are only interested in the brightness value (represented by Y), there is one single calculation to be done: `Y = (299*R + 587*G + 114*B)/1000`. The Java code for that would look like this:

    public static Color getContrastColor(Color color) {
      double y = (299 * color.getRed() + 587 * color.getGreen() + 114 * color.getBlue()) / 1000;
      return y &gt;= 128 ? Color.black : Color.white;
    }

You can see that it simply decides to use black or white, based upon the brightness of the original color. And the result works very nice in my opinion. The weights (299, 587, 114) are proportional to the sensitivity of the eyes (or rather the sensitivity of the retina) to the corresponding color.


